# Queriva — Code Quality Rules

Applies to all code in all packages. These define production quality for
a sole-developer project that will be shown to Upwork clients and used
as a portfolio piece.

---

## SECTION A — Universal (all languages)

### A1 — No dead code
No commented-out code, unused imports, or unused variables.
Temporary disables need a comment with issue number:
`// TODO: re-enable after #42`

### A2 — No magic numbers or strings
All constants must be named. No inline thresholds, ports, URLs, model
names, collection names, or timeout values.

```java
// BAD
if (score > 0.60) { }
// GOOD
if (score > minScore) { }  // minScore from @Value("${search.min-score:0.60}")
```

```python
# BAD
if score > 0.60:
# GOOD
if score > min_score:  # from os.getenv("SEARCH_MIN_SCORE", "0.60")
```

### A3 — Every public method has a docstring or Javadoc
One sentence minimum. Required for: controllers, services, loaders,
CLI entry points, public utility methods.

### A4 — Fail fast, fail loud
Validate inputs at the entry point. Raise immediately with a descriptive
message. Never silently swallow errors or return null/None where a value
is expected.

### A5 — Single responsibility
- Classes: one clear responsibility, ≤ 300 lines
- Methods: one thing, ≤ 30 lines
- If a method needs a comment explaining phases, split it

### A6 — Meaningful names, no abbreviations
No `tmp`, `val`, `obj`, `data`, `mgr`, `svc`, `res`, `q`, `col`.

```java
// BAD
List<Map<String, Object>> res = svc.search(q, col);
// GOOD
List<SearchHit> searchHits = qdrantSearchService.search(query, collection);
```

### A7 — Error messages are actionable
Every exception tells the caller what went wrong AND what to do.

```java
// BAD
throw new RuntimeException("Embed failed");
// GOOD
throw new EmbedSidecarException(
    "Embed sidecar returned 503 for model '" + model + "'. " +
    "Verify embed-sidecar is running: GET http://embed-sidecar:8001/api/health"
);
```

### A8 — No silent nulls in public APIs
Use `Optional<T>` in Java. Raise an exception in Python. Return empty
collections, not null/None, for list results.

